<section xml:id="s_limits_naive" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Introduction to limits</title>
    <objectives>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Give an informal definition of the limit of a function <m>f</m> at a given value. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Investigate the existence and/or value of a limit from a graph or table.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Give an informal definition of one-sided limits.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Express existence of two-sided limit in terms of one-sided limits.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Determine one-sided limits from a graph or table.
                    </p>
                </li>

            </ol>
    </objectives>
    
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-naive-definition-of-limit">
        <title>Informal definition of the limit</title>
        <p>
            Many of the questions we will study in regard to functions revolve around how the output of a function <m>f</m> changes with respect to its input. As such we want to develop useful and precise language and tools for describing this relation. The <em>limit</em> of a function, defined informally here and rigorously later, is one such tool. Before getting to its informal definition, we illustrate with a graphical example the type of statements we wish to formalize with limit language.
        </p> 
        
        
            <example xml:id="eg_function_behavior">
                <title>Function behavior</title>
                <statement>
                  <p>  Suppose <m>f</m> is the function whose graph is given below.
                  </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig_limit_naive">
                <caption>Graph of function <m>f</m></caption>
                <image width="70%">
                    <shortdescription>Graph of complicated function</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                 \begin{tikzpicture}
                %\draw[very thin,color=lightgray] (-3.2,-4.1) grid (6.2,4.1);
                \draw[->] (-3.2,0) -- (4.2,0) node[right] {$x$};
                \draw[->] (-2,-2.2) -- (-2,4.2) node[above] {$y$};
                \draw[-,color=blue,smooth,domain=-3:-1.16] plot ({\x},{\x/(20*pow({\x+1},2))});
                \draw[-,color=blue, smooth,domain=-0.86:0] plot ({\x},{\x/(20*pow({\x+1},2))});
                \fill[color=blue] (0,0) circle (0.05cm);
                \draw[color=blue] (0,1) circle (0.05cm);
                \draw[-,color=blue,smooth,domain=0.02:1] plot ({\x},{2*sin(1.5708*\x r)+1});
                \fill[color=blue] (1,3) circle (0.05cm);
                \draw[-,color=blue,smooth,domain=1.05:1.95,samples=2000] plot ({\x},{3+sin(pow((1/(\x-1)),1.5) r)});
                \draw[-,color=blue,smooth,domain=2.05:4.1,samples=2000] plot ({\x},{3+sin(pow((1/(\x-1)),1.5) r)});
                \draw[color=blue] (2,{3+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)}) circle (0.05cm);
                \draw[-] (-1,-0.1) -- (-1,0.1) node[above] {$a$};
                \draw[dashed] (-1,0) -- (-1,-2);
                \draw[-] (0,-0.1) node[below] {$b$} -- (0,0.1);
                \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,0.95);
                \draw[dashed] (-2,2) node[left] {$B$} -- (0.3398,{2*sin(1.5708*0.3398 r)+1});
                \draw[dashed] (-2,1) node[left] {$A$} -- (-0.05,1);
                \draw[dashed] (0.3398,0) -- (0.3398,{2*sin(1.5708*0.3398 r)+1});
                \draw[-] (0.3398,-0.1) node[below] {$c$} -- (0.3398,0.1) ;
                \draw[-] (1,-0.1) -- (1,0.1) node[below] {$d$};
                \draw[dashed] (-2,3) node[left] {$C$} -- (1,3);
                \draw[dashed] (1,0) -- (1,3);
                \draw[dashed] (-2,{3+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)}) node[left] {$D$} -- (1.95,{3+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)});
                \draw[dashed,color=black] (2,0) -- (2,{2.95+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)});
                \fill[color=blue] (2,{3.5+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)}) circle (0.05cm);
                \draw[-] (2,-0.1) node[below] {$e$} -- (2,0.1);
                \node at (3.5,2.6) {$y=f(x)$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
        </figure>
        <p>Describe how the output <m>f(x)</m> behaves as the input <m>x</m> approaches each of the values <m>a,b,c,d,e</m>. For some of these values, you might consider how <m>x</m> approaches from the left and right separately. 
        </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                As <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m>, either from the left or right, the values <m>f(x)</m> of the function get arbitrarily large and negative. 
            </p>
            <p>
                As <m>x</m> approaches <m>b</m> from the left, the values <m>f(x)</m> of <m>f</m> get closer and closer to <m>0</m>. However, as <m>x</m> approaches <m>b</m> from the right, the values <m>f(x)</m> get closer and closer to <m>A</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                As <m>x</m> approaches <m>c</m> from the left or right, the values <m>f(x)</m> of the function approach the real number <m>M</m>. We also happen to have <m>f(c)=B</m>: <ie/>, the value of <m>f</m> at <m>x=c</m> is equal to <m>B</m>.  
            </p>
            <p>
                As <m>x</m> approaches <m>d</m> from the left, the values <m>f(x)</m> of the function approach <m>C</m>. However, as <m>x</m> approaches <m>d</m> from the right, the values <m>f(x)</m> oscillate wildly above and below <m>C</m> and do not seem to approach any single value.  
            </p>
            <p>
                As <m>x</m> approaches <m>e</m> from the left or right, the values <m>f(x)</m> of the function approach <m>D</m>. Interestingly, however, the actual value of <m>f</m> at the input <m>x=e</m> is not equal to <m>D</m>. 
            </p>
        </solution>
        </example>
        <p>
            As <xref ref="eg_function_behavior"/> illustrates, an English description of how a function behaves for inputs near a given value can be quite a mouthful. Consider the limit notation introduced below as a means of making these descriptions much more concise. Roughly speaking, we will write 
            <me>
                \lim\limits_{x\to a}f(x)=L
            </me>
            to say that the values of <m>f</m> approach <m>L</m> as the input <m>x</m> appraoches <m>a</m>. This is the basic gist of <xref ref="d_limit_informal"/>, though it takes a little more care in the setup.
            
        </p>
        <definition xml:id="d_limit_informal">
            <title>Limit (informal)</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Suppose <m>f</m> is a function defined everywhere on an open interval containing the point <m>a\in \R</m>, except possibly at <m>a</m> itself. We say that the <term>limit</term> of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> exists if there is a value <m>L</m> such that the function value <m>f(x)</m> can be made arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> provided <m>x</m> is sufficiently close (but not equal) to <m>a</m>. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    When this is the case, we call <m>L</m> the limit of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> and write 
                    <men xml:id="eq_limit_informal">
                        \lim_{x\to a}f(x)=L
                    </men>.
                    When the limit does not exist we will say that <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a}f(x)</m> does not exist. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <remark>
            <title>Limit definition (informal)</title>
            <p>
                You might be thinking that our so-called informal limit definition has quite a formal ring to it. What prevents it from being a rigorous, formal definition? The issue lies precisely in making mathematical sense of the phrases <q>arbitrarily close</q> and <q>sufficiently close</q>. As intuitive as those notions may seem, we need a precise mathematical definition of them if we have any hope of building a theory on solid foundations. That is the motivation behind our formal definition <xref ref="d_lim_formal"/>, which we will meet soon.  
            </p>
        </remark>
        <example>
            <title>Limit description of graph</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>f</m> be the function with graph given in <xref ref="fig_limit_naive"/>. Use the language and notation of limits to describe the behavior of <m>f</m> for inputs <m>x</m> near the values <m>a,b,c,d,e</m>. 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The limit <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a}f(x)</m> does not exist. There is no value <m>L</m> that <m>f(x)</m> approaches for inputs <m>x</m> sufficiently close to <m>a</m>. Indeed, as <m>x</m> gets arbitrarily close to <m>a</m>, <m>f(x)</m> becomes arbitrarily large and negative. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    The limit <m>\lim\limits_{x\to b}f(x)</m> does not exist. If <m>x</m> is arbitrarily close to <m>b</m>, and less than <m>b</m> (to the left), then the values <m>f(x)</m> gets arbitrarily close to <m>0</m>; thus if the limit existed it would have to be equal to <m>0</m>. And yet for inputs <m>x</m> arbitrarily close to <m>b</m> but greater than <m>b</m> (to the right), the values <m>f(x)</m> are greater than <m>1</m>: <ie/>, they get no closer than a distance of <m>1</m> from the value <m>0</m>. This implies <m>0</m> is not the limit, and hence that no limit exists. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    We have <m>\lim\limits_{x\to c}f(x)=B</m>. Since <m>B=f(c)</m>, we have <m>\lim\limits_{x\to c}f(x)=f(c)</m> in this case. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    The limit <m>\lim\limits_{x\to d}f(x)</m> does not exist. See the explanation in <xref ref="eg_function_behavior"/>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    We have <m>\lim\limits_{x\to e}f(x)=D</m>. Note that in this case <m>e</m> is an element of the domain and <m>\lim\limits_{x\to e}f(x)\ne f(e)</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <title>Limit as compared to value</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                Provide graphs of the following functions on their entire implied domain:
                <md>
                    <mrow>f(x) \amp =\frac{x^2-1}{x-1} \amp g(x)\amp=\begin{cases}
                    x+1 \amp \text{if } x\ne 1\\
                    1  \amp \text{if } x=1
                    \end{cases}
                    \amp h(x)\amp =x+1
                    </mrow>
                </md>.
                For each function discuss the limit behavior at <m>x=1</m> as compared with the value of the function at <m>x=1</m>. 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The domain of <m>f</m> is <m>\{x\in \R\mid x\ne 0\}</m>. Since <m>f(x)=(x-1)(x+1)/(x-1)=x+1</m> for all <m>x\ne 1</m>, the graph of <m>f</m> is the line <m>y=x+1</m> for all <m>x\ne 1</m>. Similar reasoning for <m>g</m> and <m>h</m> yields the graphs below. 
                </p>
                <sbsgroup widths="">
                <sidebyside>
                <figure xml:id="fig_limit_f">
                    <caption>Graph of <m>f</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <shortdescription>Graph of f</shortdescription>
                        <sageplot>
                            f=plot((x^2-1)/(x-1), x,-1,.95)
                            g=plot((x^2-1)/(x-1), x,1.05,2)
                            P=circle((1,2),.05)
                            f+g+P
                        </sageplot>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <figure xml:id="fig_limit_g">
                    <caption>Graph of <m>g</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <shortdescription>Graph of g</shortdescription>
                        <sageplot>
                            f=plot((x^2-1)/(x-1), x,-1,.95)
                            g=plot((x^2-1)/(x-1), x,1.05,2)
                            P=circle((1,2),.05)
                            Q=point((1,1), size=70)
                            f+g+P+Q
                        </sageplot>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
                <sidebyside width="50%">
                <figure xml:id="fig_limit_h">
                    <caption>Graph of <m>h</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <shortdescription>Graph of h</shortdescription>
                        <sageplot>
                            f=plot((x^2-1)/(x-1), x,-1,.95)
                            g=plot((x^2-1)/(x-1), x,1.05,2)
                            P=circle((1,2),.05)
                            Q=point((1,2), size=70)
                            f+g+P+Q
                        </sageplot>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
            </sbsgroup>
        </solution>
        </example>
    <p>
        The basic idea behind the limit is to observe how the outputs <m>f(x)</m> change as the input <m>x</m> approaches some value <m>a</m>, written <m>x\to a</m> for short. As we saw above, a detailed graph can give a strong indication of whether the values <m>f(x)</m> approach some fixed value <m>L</m>. This type of behavior can also be made evident by a sufficiently detailed table of values. 
    </p>
    <example xml:id="eg_limit_table">
        <title>Limits: using table of values</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the function
          <me>
            h(x) = \frac{x-3}{x^3 - 3 x^2 - 2 x + 6}
          </me>.
          You can verify for your self that <m>3</m> is a root of the denominator of <m>h</m>, and hence that <m>h</m> is not defined at <m>x=3</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    What does the table of values below suggest about <m>\lim_{x\to 3}h(x)</m>? Do you think the limit exists? If so, estimate its value.
        </p>
        <table xml:id="tab_taalmansec1-1ex43">
          <title>Table of values of <m>h</m></title>
          <tabular>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2.9</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2.99</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2.999</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3.001</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3.01</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3.1</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>h(x)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.156</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.144</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.14298</m></cell>
              <cell><m>*</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.14273</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.142</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.131</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
                
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Perform some algebra on <m>h</m> to get a better idea of what <m>h(x)</m> is for <m>x\ne 3</m>. Does this algebra suggest a potential exact value for <m>\lim\limits_{x\to 3}h(x)</m>?  
                </p>
            </li>
          </ol> 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        First note that the table provides values <m>h(x)</m> for inputs <m>x</m> that get reasonably close to <m>3</m>: from the left, we have the sequence of inputs <m>2.9, 2.99, 2.999</m>, and from the right we have the sequence <m>3.1, 3.01, 3.001</m>. The closest inputs included in the table are <m>2.999</m> and <m>3.001</m>, which are a distance of 
                        <me>
                            .001=\abs{3.0001-3}=\abs{2.999-3}
                        </me>
                        away from <m>3</m>. Moreover, we notice that as these inputs get closer to <m>3</m>, the outputs <m>h(x)</m> seem to approach a value between <m>0.142</m> and <m>0.143</m>. Thus, we are inclined to believe that the limit <m>\lim\limits_{x\to 3}h(x)</m> does indeed exist, and that 
                        <me>
                            0.142 \leq \lim\limits_{x\to 3}h(x) \leq 0.143 
                        </me>.
                         In fact, since the values <m>h(x)</m> decrease as <m>x</m> approaches from the left, and increase as <m>x</m> approaches from the right, we might further guess that
                         <me>
                            0.14273 \leq \lim\limits_{x\to 3}h(x) \leq 0.14298
                        </me>.
                        Notice, however, that that guess would be conditioned on the assumption that <m>h</m> is decreasing for all <m>x</m> sufficiently close to <m>3</m> on the left, and all <m>x</m> sufficiently close to <m>x</m> on the right; and this is an assumption we are not in a position to verify at the moment.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        We can factor the denominator of <m>h</m> as 
                        <me>
                            x^3 - 3 x^2 - 2 x + 6 = (x-3)(x^2-2)
                        </me>, 
                        which means that we have 
                        <me>
                            h(x)=\frac{1}{x^2-2}
                        </me>
                        for all <m>x\ne 3</m> in the domain of <m>h</m>. Let <m>g(x)=\frac{1}{x^2-2}</m>. Since <m>h(x)=g(x)</m> for all <m>x\ne 3</m>, the limit behaviors of the two functions are the same at <m>x=3</m>. Note that <m>g</m> is defined at <m>x=3</m> and satisfies 
                        <me>
                            g(3)=\frac{1}{9-2}=\frac{1}{7}\approx 0.142857
                        </me>.
                        Wait a minute, that looks a whole lot like our estimate of 
                        <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a}h(x)</m> in part (a)! Are we in a position to say with assurance that 
                        <me>
                            \lim\limits_{x\to 3}h(x)=\frac{1}{7}?
                        </me>
                        Not quite yet, but the evidence is stacking up. We could conclude this if we knew that <m>\lim\limits{x\to 3}g(x)=1/7</m>. This seems like it should be true since <m>g</m> is actually defined at <m>x=3</m> and we have seen that rational functions behave <q>nicely</q> around points in their domain. Soon we will have a more precise way of saying this that will give us the answer we desire.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_def">
        <title>One-sided limits</title>
        <p>
            Let's look at the limit behavior of the sign function 
            <me>
                \sgn(x)=\begin{cases}
                1\amp \text{if } x&gt; 0 \\
                -1\amp \text{if } x&lt; 0\\
                0\amp \text{if } x=0.
                \end{cases}
            </me>
            near <m>x=0</m>. (See <xref ref="fig_signfunc"/>.)  Since the function is defined piecwise, it is natural to look at the behavior for <m>x&gt; 0</m> and <m>x&lt; 0</m> separately. Since <m>f(x)=1</m> for all <m>x&gt; 0</m>, we conclude that <m>f(x)</m> approaches <m>1</m> for all <m>x</m> sufficiently close to <m>0</m> and lying <em>to its right</em>. Similarly, we see that <m>f(x)</m> approaches <m>-1</m> for all <m>x</m> sufficiently close to <m>0</m> and lying <em>to its left</em>. Wouldn't it be nice if we had some notation to capture this <q>from the left</q> and <q>from the right</q> behavior? The notion of <em>one-sided limits</em>, defined below, gives us just what we need. In particular, using its notation, we can say more succinctly that 
            <md>
                <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to 0^+}\sgn(x) \amp =1</mrow>
                <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to 0^-}\sgn(x) \amp =-1</mrow>
            </md>.
            Before getting to that definition, let's finish our analysis of the behavior of <m>\sgn</m> near <m>x=0</m>.  Since the values of <m>\sgn</m> approach two distinct values (<m>1</m> and <m>-1</m>), depending on whether <m>x</m> approaches <m>0</m> from the right or left, we conclude that there is no <em>single value</em> that values <m>\sgn(x)</m> approach as <m>x</m> gets sufficiently close to <m>0</m>, and hence that <m>\lim\limits_{x\to 0}\sgn(x)</m> does not exist. (We make this reasoning more official in <xref ref="th_limit_left_right"/>.) 
        </p>
    <definition xml:id="d_one_sided_limits">
        <title>One-sided limits: informal</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>f</m> be a function, and let <m>a\in \R</m>.  
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <title>Left-hand limit</title>
                        <p>
                            Assume <m>f</m> is defined on an open interval of the form <m>(c,a)</m>. We say the <term>left-hand limit</term> of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from the left exists if there is a value <m>L</m> such that <m>f(x)</m> can be made arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> provided <m>x</m> is sufficiently close to <m>a</m> and lying to its left. 
                        </p>
                        <p> When this is the case we call <m>L</m> the <term>left-hand limit</term> of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from the left, and write 
                            <me>
                                \lim_{x\to a^-}f(x)=L
                            </me>.
                        When no such <m>L</m> exists, we say that the left-hand limit <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^-}f(x)</m> does not exist. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Right-hand limit</title>
                        <p>
                            Assume <m>f</m> is defined on an open interval of the form <m>(a,d)</m>. We say the <term>right-hand limit</term> of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from the right exists if there is a value <m>L</m> such that <m>f(x)</m> can be made arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> provided <m>x</m> is sufficiently close to <m>a</m> and lying to its right.
                        </p>
                        <p> When this is the case we call <m>L</m> the <term>right-hand limit</term> of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from the right, and write 
                            <me>
                                \lim_{x\to a^+}f(x)=L
                            </me>.
                        When no such <m>L</m> exists, we say that the right-hand limit <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^+}f(x)</m> does not exist. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="eg_one_sided_graph">
        <title>Visualizing one-sided limits</title>
        <statement>
          <p>  Suppose <m>f</m> is the function whose graph is given below.
          </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_limit_naive_one_sided">
        <caption>Graph of function <m>f</m></caption>
        <image width="70%">
            <shortdescription>Graph of complicated function</shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
         \begin{tikzpicture}
        %\draw[very thin,color=lightgray] (-3.2,-4.1) grid (6.2,4.1);
        \draw[->] (-3.2,0) -- (4.2,0) node[right] {$x$};
        \draw[->] (-2,-2.2) -- (-2,4.2) node[above] {$y$};
        \draw[-,color=blue,smooth,domain=-3:-1.16] plot ({\x},{\x/(20*pow({\x+1},2))});
        \draw[-,color=blue, smooth,domain=-0.86:0] plot ({\x},{\x/(20*pow({\x+1},2))});
        \fill[color=blue] (0,0) circle (0.05cm);
        \draw[color=blue] (0,1) circle (0.05cm);
        \draw[-,color=blue,smooth,domain=0.02:1] plot ({\x},{2*sin(1.5708*\x r)+1});
        \fill[color=blue] (1,3) circle (0.05cm);
        \draw[-,color=blue,smooth,domain=1.05:1.95,samples=2000] plot ({\x},{3+sin(pow((1/(\x-1)),1.5) r)});
        \draw[-,color=blue,smooth,domain=2.05:4.1,samples=2000] plot ({\x},{3+sin(pow((1/(\x-1)),1.5) r)});
        \draw[color=blue] (2,{3+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)}) circle (0.05cm);
        \draw[-] (-1,-0.1) -- (-1,0.1) node[above] {$a$};
        \draw[dashed] (-1,0) -- (-1,-2);
        \draw[-] (0,-0.1) node[below] {$b$} -- (0,0.1);
        \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,0.95);
        \draw[dashed] (-2,2) node[left] {$B$} -- (0.3398,{2*sin(1.5708*0.3398 r)+1});
        \draw[dashed] (-2,1) node[left] {$A$} -- (-0.05,1);
        \draw[dashed] (0.3398,0) -- (0.3398,{2*sin(1.5708*0.3398 r)+1});
        \draw[-] (0.3398,-0.1) node[below] {$c$} -- (0.3398,0.1) ;
        \draw[-] (1,-0.1) -- (1,0.1) node[below] {$d$};
        \draw[dashed] (-2,3) node[left] {$C$} -- (1,3);
        \draw[dashed] (1,0) -- (1,3);
        \draw[dashed] (-2,{3+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)}) node[left] {$D$} -- (1.95,{3+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)});
        \draw[dashed,color=black] (2,0) -- (2,{2.95+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)});
        \fill[color=blue] (2,{3.5+sin(pow((1/1),1.5) r)}) circle (0.05cm);
        \draw[-] (2,-0.1) node[below] {$e$} -- (2,0.1);
        \node at (3.5,2.6) {$y=f(x)$};
