</image>
</figure>
<p>
    Describe the behavior of <m>f</m> near the inputs <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>d</m>, and <m>e</m> using one-sided limit notation. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
    <p>
        <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
        Neither <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^-}f(x)</m> nor <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^+}f(x)</m> exists, since the function values get arbitrarily large (and negative) as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from either side. 
    </p>
</li>
    <li><p>
        We have 
        <md>
            <mrow>\lim_{x\to b^-}f(x) \amp = 0 \amp \lim_{x\to b^+}f(x)\amp =A</mrow>
        </md>.
        Thus in this case the left- and right-handed limits of <m>f</m> both exist, but do not agree. 
    </p></li>
    <li><p>
        We have <m>\lim\limits_{x\to d^-}f(x)=C</m>. By contrast, <m>\lim\limits_{x\to d^+}f(x)</m> does not exist as the values of <m>f</m> oscillate wildly as <m>x</m> approaches <m>d</m> from the right.
    </p></li>
    <li><p>
        We have 
        <me>\lim\limits_{x\to e^-}f(x)=\lim\limits_{x\to e^+}f(x)=D</me>.
    </p></li>
</ul>
</p>
</solution>
</example>
<p>
    As was suggested by <xref ref="eg_one_sided_graph"/> and made official by the next theorem, <m>\lim_{x\to a}f(x)</m> exists if and only if both one-sided limits exist and are equal. 
</p>
<theorem xml:id="th_limit_left_right">
    <title>One-sided limits test</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
           Suppose <m>f</m> is a function defined everywhere on an open interval containing the point <m>a\in \R</m>, except possibly at <m>a</m> itself. The limit <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a}f(x)</m> exists if and only if the following conditions hold.
           <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The one-sided limits <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^-}f(x)</m> and <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^+}f(x)</m> exist.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^-}f(x)=\lim\limits_{x\to a^+}f(x)</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
           </ol> 
           When this the case, we have 
           <me>
            \lim\limits_{x\to a}f(x)=\lim_{x\to a^-}f(x)=\lim_{x\to a^+}f(x)=L
           </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
           As a consequence, if one of the one-sided limits does not exist, or if both one-sided limits exist but are not equal to one another, then the limit <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a}f(x)</m> does not exist. 
        </p>
    </statement>
</theorem>
<p>
    <xref ref="th_limit_left_right"/> is particularly useful in that it gives us a convenient means of showing that a limit does <em>not</em> exist. Let's apply this theorem to some of our previous examples and see how it simplifies things. 
</p>
<p>
    Looking again at the sign function, we see that the left and right limits do indeed exist, but are not equal: we have 
    <md>
        <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to 0^-}\sgn(x)\amp =-1  </mrow>
        <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to 0^+}\sgn(x) \amp =1 </mrow>
    </md>.
    Since <m>\lim\limits_{x\to 0^-}\sgn(x)\ne \lim\limits_{x\to 0^+}\sgn(x)</m>, we conclude that <m>\lim\limits_{x\to 0}\sgn(x)</m> does not exist. 
</p>
<p>
    Now return to the function <m>f</m> whose graph is given in <xref ref="eg_one_sided_graph"/>, and let's see how we can apply <xref ref="th_limit_left_right"/> at some of the limit points. Since 
    <md>
        <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to b^-}f(x) \amp = 0 </mrow>
        <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to b^+}f(x) \amp = A\ne 0  </mrow>
    </md>,
    we conclude that <m>\lim\limits_{x\to b}f(x)</m> does not exist. By contrast since 
    <md>
        <mrow>\lim\limits_{x\to e^-}f(x) \amp = \lim\limits_{x\to e^+}f(x)=D </mrow>
    </md>,
    we conclude that <m>\lim\limits_{x\to e}f(x)</m> exists and that
    <me>
        \lim\limits_{x\to e}f(x)=\lim\limits_{x\to e^-}f(x)=\lim\limits_{x\to e^+}f(x)=D
    </me>.
</p>

<p>
    We end our section by extending somewhat our definition of the limit. 
    Previously our definition of limit only applied to points <m>a\in \R</m> for which the function was defined for all <m>x\ne a</m> on an open interval <m>(c,d)</m> containing <m>a</m>. The language of one-sided limits allows us to extend this definition to <q>endpoints</q> of the domain, as the next definition makes clear. <xref ref="th_limit_left_right"/> guarantees that this definition is a consistent extension of <xref ref="d_limit_informal"/>.    
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_limit_extended">
    <title>Limit at endpoints of domain</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>f</m> be a function, and let <m>a\in \R</m>. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <title>Right endpoint</title>
                    <p>
                        If <m>f</m> is defined for all <m>x</m> on an open interval <m>(c,a)</m>, but not for all <m>x\ne a</m> in a full open interval containing <m>a</m>, then we say the limit of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> exists if <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^-}f(x)</m> exists. When this is the case, we define 
                        <me>
                            \lim_{x\to a}f(x)=\lim_{x\to a^-}f(x)
                        </me>. 
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Left endpoint</title>
                    <p>
                        If <m>f</m> is defined for all <m>x</m> on an open interval <m>(a,d)</m>, but not for all <m>x\ne a</m> in a full open interval containing <m>a</m>, then we say the limit of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> exists if <m>\lim\limits_{x\to a^+}f(x)</m> exists. When this is the case, we define 
                        <me>
                            \lim_{x\to a}f(x)=\lim_{x\to a^+}f(x)
                        </me>. 
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>


